lesson.title: Data and Tables
lesson.summary: Learn the principles behind relational data organization: tables, queries, aggregations, keys, and joins.

atoms.title: arst
atoms.text:
This video shows the results of a **count** aggregation on the **animals** table. It's a **count** aggregation, grouping the values in the table using the **species** column. In other words, it's counting the number of rows that have the same value in that column.

Here's the table we start with:

| **name** *string* | **species** *string* | **birthdate** *date* |
| --- | --- | ---|
| Max | gorilla | 2001-04-13 |
| Sue | gorilla | 1998-06-12 |
| Max | moose | 2012-02-20 | 
| Alison | llama | 1997-11-24 |
| George | gorilla | 2011-01-09 |
| Spot | iguana | 2010-07-23 | 
| Ratu | orangutan | 1989-09-15 |
| Eli | llama | 2002-02-22 |

And here's the result of the aggregation:

| **species** *string* | **count** *integer* |
| --- | --- |
| gorilla | 3 |
| moose | 1 |
| llama | 2 |
| iguana | 1 |
| orangutan | 1 |

atoms.title: ars
atoms.text:
In a relational database, when there are multiple answers to a question (like "What do brown bears eat?") they will usually appear as multiple rows in a table.

Here's the table from this quiz:

**diet:**

| **species** *string* | **food** *string* |
| --- | --- |
| llama | plants |
| brown bear | fish |
| brown bear | meat |
| brown bear | plants |
| orangutan | plants |
| orangutan | insects |

atoms.title: arst
atoms.text:
Here are the tables from this video.

The **pictures** table stores the names of cute animals and the filenames of their pictures.

| **id** | **name** | **filename** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 1 | Fluffy | fluffsocute.jpg |
| 2 | Monster | monstie-basket.png |
| 3 | George | george.jpg |
| ... | ... | ... |

The **votes** table stores information about which pictures have been displayed together, and which one the user voted for:

| **left** | **right** | **winner** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| 2 | 3 | 3 |
| 1 | 3 | 1 |
| 2 | 1 | 1 |
| 3 | 2 | 3 |
| 3 | 1 | 1 |
| 2 | 3 | 3 |
| ... | ... | ... |

We can ask the database to **join** these tables, to look up the animal names for each of the votes:

| **left_name** | **right_name** | **winner_name** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Monster | George | George |
| Fluffy | George  | George |
| Monster | Fluffy | Fluffy |
| George | Monster | George |
| George | Fluffy | Fluffy |
| Monster | George | George |
| ... | ... | ... |

atoms.title: arst
atoms.text:
The examples in the video are not made up! [There actually are five Springfields in the state of Wisconsin.](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Springfield,_Wisconsin)

Country names are not actually as unique as I said in the video, though. There's only one France, but there are two Congos. That is, as of 2016 there are two countries often called "Congo": the *Democratic Republic of the Congo*, also known as Congo-Kinshasa and previously known as Zaire; and the *Republic of the Congo*, also known as Congo-Brazzaville.

A better primary key for countries exists, though: the international community has established standard [country codes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166), unique abbreviations for each country. Congo-Kinshasa has country code `CD`, while Congo-Brazzaville is `CG`. These are also their Internet top-level domain names.

atoms.title: a
atoms.text:
In the video, there are two tables, **animals** and **diet**. Joining those tables gives us a new table, which contains information taken from the two original tables. The join statement has a *join condition* that tells the database how to match up the rows from one table with the rows from the other.

----

# Table reference

Here are the tables from the video. They're the same ones as earlier in this lesson.

**animals:**

| **name** *string* | **species** *string* | **birthdate** *date* |
| --- | --- | ---|
| Max | gorilla | 2001-04-13 |
| Sue | gorilla | 1998-06-12 |
| Max | moose | 2012-02-20 | 
| Alison | llama | 1997-11-24 |
| George | gorilla | 2011-01-09 |
| Spot | iguana | 2010-07-23 |
| Ratu | orangutan | 1989-09-15 |
| Eli | llama | 2002-02-22 |

**diet:**

| **species** *string* | **food** *string* |
| --- | --- |
| llama | plants |
| brown bear | fish |
| brown bear | meat |
| brown bear | plants |
| orangutan | plants |
| orangutan | insects |

----

This SQL query will join the two tables to find out what foods each animal can eat:

```sql
select animals.name, animals.species, diet.food
       from animals join diet
       on animals.species = diet.species;
```

You'll see much more with these tables later in the course!
